'''Yamaga Onsen''' (やまがおんせん) is a [[:en:Onsen|Onsen]] located in [[:en:Kumamoto Prefecture|Kumamoto Prefecture]][[:en:Yamaga, Kumamoto|Yamaga City]] (formerly part of [[:en:Higo Province|Higo Province]]). It is renowned for the annual "Yamaga Lantern Festival" ({{ill|Yamaga Tōrō Matsuri|ja|山鹿灯籠まつり|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaga Tōrō Matsuri|qq=|1=Yamaga Lantern Festival|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11471245}}) held every August. A communal bath (public bath) known as {{ill|Sakura-yu|ja|さくら湯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakura-yu|qq=|1=Sakura-yu (Yamaga)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q129996964}} is available.

== Spring Quality ==
* Alkaline simple hot spring

It is reputed for its exceptionally smooth water that is said to have excellent beautifying effects.

== Hot Spring Town ==
[[File:yamaga_ashiyu.jpg|thumb|"Ashiyu"]]

There are approximately 20 establishments including [[:en:Ryokan|ryokan]] and [[:en:Hotel|hotels]], making it one of the largest hot spring towns in Kumamoto Prefecture. As an old hot spring town, it emphasizes its historic charm, and it is said that during the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji period]] it was modeled after [[:en:Dōgo Onsen|Dogo Onsen]]. Although it is located within the urban area, creatively designed open-air baths and bathing rooms enhance its quaint atmosphere. In addition to "Ashiyu" and communal baths, a hot spring pool (now no longer extant) was once established. Along the former {{ill|Buzen Highway|ja|豊前街道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buzen Highway|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, there stands the Yachiyo-za, a theater building completed in 1910 (Meiji 45).

=== Communal Bath ===
A communal bath known as {{ill|Sakura-yu|ja|さくら湯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakura-yu|qq=|1=Sakura-yu (Yamaga)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q129996964}} exists. It was originally constructed by inviting the master carpenter who built the main building of {{ill|Dogo Onsen Honkan|ja|道後温泉本館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dogo Onsen Honkan|qq=|1=Dōgo Onsen Honkan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11641713}}.

In a redevelopment in 1973 (Shōwa 48), it was incorporated into the Plaza Five Building, preserving only the original eave ([[:en:Bargeboard|hafu]]).{{Citation needed範囲|The interior was modern and at first resembled a pool, yet the water flowing from the lion-shaped spout retained the characteristic smoothness of Yamaga Onsen.|date=2024-08}}

In July 2011 (Heisei 23), redevelopment work on the Plaza Five Building commenced, and in October 2012 (Heisei 24) a restoration of traditional Japanese architecture was completed.{{独自研究範囲|Primarily used by local residents.|date=2024-08}}{{Citation needed範囲|A drinking facility existed in front of the old building’s entrance, providing potable hot spring water 24 hours a day.|date=2024-08}}

