'''Yamaga Onsen''' (やまがおんせん) is a {{ill|Onsen|en|Onsen|WD=Q655311|lt=Onsen|1=Onsen}} located in {{ill|Kumamoto Prefecture|en|Kumamoto Prefecture|WD=Q130308|lt=Kumamoto Prefecture|1=Kumamoto Prefecture}}{{ill|Yamaga, Kumamoto|en|Yamaga, Kumamoto|WD=Q861214|lt=Yamaga City|1=Yamaga, Kumamoto}} (formerly part of {{ill|Higo Province|en|Higo Province|WD=Q259705|lt=Higo Province|1=Higo Province}}). It is renowned for the annual "Yamaga Lantern Festival" ({{ill|Yamaga Tōrō Matsuri|ja|山鹿灯籠まつり|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaga Tōrō Matsuri|1=Yamaga Lantern Festival|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11471245}}) held every August. A communal bath (public bath) known as {{ill|Sakura-yu|ja|さくら湯|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakura-yu|1=Sakura-yu (Yamaga)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q129996964}} is available.

== Spring Quality ==
* Alkaline simple hot spring

It is reputed for its exceptionally smooth water that is said to have excellent beautifying effects.

== Hot Spring Town ==
[[File:yamaga_ashiyu.jpg|thumb|"Ashiyu"]]

There are approximately 20 establishments including {{ill|Ryokan|en|Ryokan|WD=Q562930|lt=ryokan|1=Ryokan}} and {{ill|Hotel|en|Hotel|WD=Q27686|lt=hotels|1=Hotel}}, making it one of the largest hot spring towns in Kumamoto Prefecture. As an old hot spring town, it emphasizes its historic charm, and it is said that during the {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|WD=Q3125096|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era}} it was modeled after {{ill|Dōgo Onsen|en|Dōgo Onsen|WD=Q1037748|lt=Dogo Onsen|1=Dōgo Onsen}}. Although it is located within the urban area, creatively designed open-air baths and bathing rooms enhance its quaint atmosphere. In addition to "Ashiyu" and communal baths, a hot spring pool (now no longer extant) was once established. Along the former {{ill|Buzen Highway|ja|豊前街道|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buzen Highway|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, there stands the Yachiyo-za, a theater building completed in 1910 (Meiji 45).

=== Communal Bath ===
A communal bath known as {{ill|Sakura-yu|ja|さくら湯|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakura-yu|1=Sakura-yu (Yamaga)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q129996964}} exists. It was originally constructed by inviting the master carpenter who built the main building of {{ill|Dogo Onsen Honkan|ja|道後温泉本館|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dogo Onsen Honkan|1=Dōgo Onsen Honkan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11641713}}.

In a redevelopment in 1973 (Shōwa 48), it was incorporated into the Plaza Five Building, preserving only the original eave ({{ill|Bargeboard|en|Bargeboard|WD=Q4881511|lt=hafu|1=Bargeboard}}).{{Citation needed範囲|The interior was modern and at first resembled a pool, yet the water flowing from the lion-shaped spout retained the characteristic smoothness of Yamaga Onsen.|date=2024-08}}

In July 2011 (Heisei 23), redevelopment work on the Plaza Five Building commenced, and in October 2012 (Heisei 24) a restoration of traditional Japanese architecture was completed.{{独自研究範囲|Primarily used by local residents.|date=2024-08}}{{Citation needed範囲|A drinking facility existed in front of the old building’s entrance, providing potable hot spring water 24 hours a day.|date=2024-08}}

